    <section>
      <h2>Fiber Gummy Ingredients: Sources, Types, and What the Science Says</h2>

      <div class="ing-box">
        <h3>Understanding Fiber Sources in Gummies</h3>
        <p>Not all fiber is created equal. The source determines the type of fiber (soluble vs. insoluble), its prebiotic activity, its digestive tolerance, and its specific health benefits. Here is a breakdown of the four primary fiber sources used in the gummies on this list:</p>

        <table class="dose-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Fiber Source</th><th>Type</th><th>Prebiotic</th><th>Key Benefits</th><th>Tolerance</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Chicory Root (Inulin)</td><td>Soluble</td><td>Yes</td><td>Microbiome support, calcium absorption, regularity</td><td>Moderate — gas possible at higher doses</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Wheat Dextrin</td><td>Soluble</td><td>Yes</td><td>Gentle regularity, prebiotic activity, blood sugar support</td><td>High — very well tolerated</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Psyllium Husk</td><td>Soluble + Insoluble</td><td>Mild</td><td>Cholesterol reduction, blood sugar, stool bulk, FDA heart claim</td><td>Moderate — requires adequate hydration</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Acacia Fiber</td><td>Soluble</td><td>Yes</td><td>Microbiome support, slow fermentation, minimal bloating</td><td>Very High — lowest gas production</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Soluble Fiber vs. Insoluble Fiber</h3>

        <p><strong>Soluble fiber</strong> dissolves in water to form a viscous, gel-like material in the gut. This gel slows the passage of food through the digestive system, which has three primary effects: it improves glucose control by reducing post-meal blood sugar spikes, it lowers LDL cholesterol by binding to bile acids and carrying them out of the body, and it feeds beneficial gut bacteria through fermentation in the colon. Chicory root inulin, wheat dextrin, and acacia fiber are all soluble fibers.</p>

        <p><strong>Insoluble fiber</strong> does not dissolve in water. It passes through the digestive system largely intact, adding bulk to stool and accelerating transit time through the colon. This mechanical action prevents constipation and reduces the time that potentially harmful substances remain in contact with the intestinal lining. Psyllium husk is unique in providing meaningful amounts of both soluble and insoluble fiber.</p>

        <p>Most fiber gummies contain primarily soluble fiber because it is easier to incorporate into a gummy matrix. This is not a limitation for most people — the typical Western diet is more deficient in soluble fiber than insoluble fiber, and the prebiotic benefits of soluble fiber are significant. However, if you specifically need insoluble fiber for stool bulk and regularity, psyllium-based Konsyl is the only gummy option, or you can increase your intake of whole grains, vegetables, and bran.</p>

        <h3>The Prebiotic Advantage</h3>

        <p>Prebiotic fiber has become the defining feature of premium fiber gummies, and the science supports the emphasis. A 2023 systematic review of 64 randomized controlled trials found that prebiotic supplementation produced the following measurable effects:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>Increased Bifidobacterium populations by 25% within 4 weeks</li>
          <li>Improved bowel frequency by an average of 1.5 additional movements per week</li>
          <li>Reduced self-reported bloating scores by 18% after the initial adjustment period</li>
          <li>Enhanced calcium absorption by 8-12% (particularly with inulin-type fructans)</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Benefiber (wheat dextrin), Vitafusion (chicory root), SmartyPants (chicory root), Nature Made (chicory root), Garden of Life (acacia), and Olly (chicory root) all provide verified prebiotic fiber. Metamucil's plant-based blend has mild prebiotic properties, and Konsyl's psyllium provides limited but measurable prebiotic activity.</p>
      </div>
